  "prompt": "Which enzyme uses both NAD+ and NADP+ as a coenzyme?",
  "response": "The enzyme that uses both NAD+ (Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide) and NADP+ (Nicotinamide Adenine Dinucleotide Phosphate) as a coenzyme is Glutamate Dehydrogenase (GDH).\n\nGlutamate Dehydrogenase is a key enzyme in amino acid metabolism that catalyzes the reversible oxidative deamination of glutamate to \u03b1-ketoglutarate. This enzyme plays a crucial role in nitrogen metabolism and can use either NAD+ or NADP+ as a cofactor, depending on the specific metabolic context and cellular conditions.\n\nKey points about Glutamate Dehydrogenase:\n1. Reversible reaction\n2. Occurs in mitochondrial matrix\n3. Important in amino acid metabolism\n4. Can utilize both NAD+ and NADP+\n5. Helps regulate nitrogen balance in cells\n\nThe ability to use both NAD+ and NADP+ makes Glutamate Dehydrogenase unique among enzymes and highlights its versatility in metabolic processes.",
